{Treating Grunfeld "Tarrasch way"} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5.
e3 {trying to Be2, O-O} 5... O-O 6. Be2 c5 {immediately attack center;  c6 is
possible, but more like Slav than Grunfeld way -  castle and b4, a4, b5}  (6...
dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 {Petrosian-Botvinnik, 5th game 1963 world championship} 8. d5
{or h3 to transpose to main lines} 8... Bg4 (8... e6 9. dxe6 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1
Bxe6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Ke2 {White has better endgame after Ng5-Nge4} ) 9. O-O {
h3, take bishop on f3 and black establishes blockade on d6, while white has
space advantage thanks to d5 pawn} ) 7. O-O cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 {Reversed Tarrasch
with extra tempo for white} 9. h3 { not allowing Bg4-Bxf3 to weaken our
isolated d-pawn. resulting simple active equal game that does not require much
theoretical knowledge} 9... dxc4 (9... Bf5 10. c5 b6 11. Bb5 { Qa4 gives white
good queenside play} )  (9... b6 {alternative mainline. white plays similar as
black would play against fianchetto, but extra tempo gives more possibilities} 
10. Ne5 {going for undefended knight} 10... Bb7 11. Bf3 {important tactical
sequence, prevents dc4, as Nc6 would be hanging} 11... Na5 12. Re1 Rc8
{tactical defense}  (12... dxc4 13. Bxb7 Nxb7 14. Nc6 {attacking e7, point or
Re1} ) 13. b3 dxc4 14. Bxb7 Nxb7 15. d5 {targeting weak c6}  (15. bxc4
{standard move} 15... Na5 {same play as Tarrasch with colors reversed} 16. Ba3
{defends c4 as e7 is undefended} 16... Re8 17. c5 {Larssen-Kasparov game with
colors reversed is a nice exaple of how to win such positions} 17... bxc5 (
17... Nd5 18. Qf3 {targets f7} 18... Nxc3 {Qxf7+ doesn't work} 19. Qxc3 bxc5
20. Bxc5 {Similar to other variations} )  (17... Nd7 18. Qe2 (18. Qf3
{targetting f7} 18... Nxe5 19. dxe5 bxc5 20. Rad1 {pawn sacrifice} 20... Qb6
21. Nd5 Qe6 22. Qe4 {giving white dominant position: black bishop is passive, 
knight is misplaced and c5 is weak} ) 18... bxc5 19. Rac1 {now it is getting
very dangerous} 19... cxd4 20. Nxf7 {long and forcing line, giving white extra
pawn in queen endgame} 20... Kxf7 21. Qe6+ Kf8 22. Ne4 {Ng5 is a treat} 22...
Bh6 23. Nf6 Nxf6 24. Rxc8 Qxc8 25. Bxe7+ Kg7 26. Bxf6+ Kf8 27. Be7+ Kg7 28.
Qe5+ Kg8 29. Qd5+ Kh8 30. Bf6+ Bg7 31. Bxg7+ Kxg7 32. Qxd4+ {picks up knight
with checks} 32... Kg8 33. Rxe8+ Qxe8 34. Qd5+ Qf7 35. Qxa5) 18. Bxc5 {white
has active pieces, but isolated pawn; dynamically balanced} 18... Nd7 19. Nxd7
Qxd7 20. Rc1 {white has strong centre on dark squares} ) 15... cxb3 {other ines
are also sharp}  (15... Re8 16. Nc6 Qd7 17. Ne5 {possible repetition} 17... Qd8
18. Qf3 cxb3 19. axb3 {good compensation as a7 is hanging and c6 is available,
